@node Introduction "digital Documentation - Introduction"

While I was searching for a chronometer worth running the whole time the
system is up, I had to see that there were no real time displayers out
there (since now :).

Some offered thousands of options, but the really interesting stuff was
missing (i.e. digital easly readable time display). Most did not allow free
font selection or window scaling / placement. Some hacked themselves into
the system to display the time in the screen's title bar. Since the
screen's title bar is the property of the screen's owner, I can't agree
with such strategies.

Well, @{b}digital@{ub} satisfies all your needs (hopefully). It comes along
with a fast freely scalable and configurable GUI (which is *not* MUI, of course,
it's @{b}SCALAR@{ub}), and does always display the @{u}true@{uu} system time.
To beat the best, it only prints texts that have changed in its GUI, so
it is really nice to the system and doesn't hurt performance in doing
superfluous stuff.

@{b}digital@{ub} was thought to be copied to your WBStartup-drawer and being
used permanently as your system's digital chronometer. Of course you can
include it in your User-Startup, too, but (de)installing it from the WBStartup
is much easier.

Created using SAS/C 6.56.

@endnode


@node Usage "digital Documentation - Usage"

@{b}digital@{ub} can be used from Workbench and from the Shell, using the
same keywords.

1> digital PS=PUBSCREEN/K,PL=POPLEFT/N/K,PT=POPTOP/N/K,PW=POPWIDTH/N/K,
           PH=POPHEIGHT/N/K,FN=FONTNAME/K,FS=FONTSIZE/K/N,TP=TOOLPRI/K/N

@{i}Example:@{ui} digital PS=Workbench POPLEFT=0 PT=10 PW=400 PH=200 FN=topaz.font FS=11

@{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} is the name of the public screen to open the window on.

@{b}POPLEFT, POPTOP, POPWIDTH and POPHEIGHT@{ub} are the numeric initial position- and
sizing parameters to use when opening the window. Be careful with them. For
your pleasure, @{b}digital@{ub} displays the current coordinates directly after
changing the position or size for a while. Please only use these coordinates
because @{b}digital@{ub} does its internal window size calculation.

@{b}FONTNAME@{ub} is the name of the font to use for the display. You can
use really every font here that makes sense. People who like big stuff may
want to use a scalable CompuGraphics (tm) font and size it to the maximum
height that will fit into the screen. People liking little stuff may choose
their favourite little designed font or could even make a little font on
their own. If you do this and want to share it with the rest of the world,
give it to me and I'll include it in one of the next releases of @{b}digital@{ub}.

@{b}FONTSIZE@{ub} is the numeric value of the height of the desired font.

@{b}TOOLPRI@{ub}, the last parameter, is the numeric value of the task
priority of @{b}digital@{ub} compared to other tasks in your system.
Zero is the default, but a higher value doesn't hurt performance because
@{b}digital@{ub} doesn't need much CPU time, only once a second.

Using one of the font-parameters only makes sense when using the other one,
too.

The recommended way for configuring @{b}digital@{ub} when running it form the WB
are tooltypes. Their usage and description are equal to those of the
Shell parameters. Check out the already set tooltypes and you'll know
how it works.

@endnode


